# -*- encoding: utf-8 -*-
# Arc: SailorArc | Scene: TheOldRoad6
# Source: C:\Program Files (x86)\Steam\steamapps\common\The Survival of Sarah Rose\game\script.rpy

translate ru strings:

    old "When they departed from the crossroads, they left behind the last of any real threats."
    new "When they departed from the crossroads, they left behind the last of any real threats."

    old "Before long, just as Sigmund predicted, the roads turned safer as they drew closer to Rahayal."
    new "Before long, just as Sigmund predicted, the roads turned safer as they drew closer to Rahayal."

    old "In the last few days, neither Sarah nor Sakar wasted what little time they had guaranteed."
    new "In the last few days, neither Sarah nor Sakar wasted what little time they had guaranteed."

    old "Each night she spend with him."
    new "Each night she spend with him."

    old "Sakar was more experienced than her, but Sarah was a fast and eager student."
    new "Sakar was more experienced than her, but Sarah was a fast and eager student."

    old "Hiding and sneaking around was pointless and soon abandoned. By the end, Sarah and Sakar vanished into the bushes with few doubts as to their intentions."
    new "Hiding and sneaking around was pointless and soon abandoned. By the end, Sarah and Sakar vanished into the bushes with few doubts as to their intentions."

    old "She saw Sigmund disaproved of her, but she didn't care much for his approval or disapproval anymore. He was not the father-figure he pretended to be."
    new "She saw Sigmund disaproved of her, but she didn't care much for his approval or disapproval anymore. He was not the father-figure he pretended to be."

    old "And so, with little sleep and a great deal of exhaustion from their frequent encounters, Sarah found herself sore and tired."
    new "And so, with little sleep and a great deal of exhaustion from their frequent encounters, Sarah found herself sore and tired."

    old "It was in that condition, seated up front on the wagon, when her eyes first fell upon the city of Rahayal."
    new "It was in that condition, seated up front on the wagon, when her eyes first fell upon the city of Rahayal."

    old "The roads grew busier and busier."
    new "The roads grew busier and busier."

    old "Before long, they were just one of many trade carts."
    new "Before long, they were just one of many trade carts."

    old "After several days of travelling in what now seemed an unfamiliar sense of safety, that Sarah's eyes first fell upon the city of Rahayal."
    new "After several days of travelling in what now seemed an unfamiliar sense of safety, that Sarah's eyes first fell upon the city of Rahayal."

    old "Rahayal."
    new "Rahayal."

    old "The capital of the Mythran empire."
    new "The capital of the Mythran empire."

    old "In all the world, there were no cities that could make a claim to be its rival."
    new "In all the world, there were no cities that could make a claim to be its rival."

    old "The empire that it represented, likewise, possessed no equal."
    new "The empire that it represented, likewise, possessed no equal."

    old "The landmass that now fell under this singular dominion was once a collection of fueding nations, not all that different from the union kingdoms that Sarah hailed from."
    new "The landmass that now fell under this singular dominion was once a collection of fueding nations, not all that different from the union kingdoms that Sarah hailed from."

    old "Flanked on one side by the central kingdoms, equal in power but more unified, and flanked on the other side by the Hyral mountains, the open and vast plains made its land vulnerable from all sides."
    new "Flanked on one side by the central kingdoms, equal in power but more unified, and flanked on the other side by the Hyral mountains, the open and vast plains made its land vulnerable from all sides."

    old "For centuries, this was the fate of this corner of the world, to be looted by its neighbours, both human and orc."
    new "For centuries, this was the fate of this corner of the world, to be looted by its neighbours, both human and orc."

    old "Its large and fertile fields lured in endless throngs of fortune seekers. But the land was nearly impossible to defend by virtue of its geography."
    new "Its large and fertile fields lured in endless throngs of fortune seekers. But the land was nearly impossible to defend by virtue of its geography."

    old "Those brave enough to try would settle. Prosper. And like a pig grown fat, slaughtered and eaten by a rival."
    new "Those brave enough to try would settle. Prosper. And like a pig grown fat, slaughtered and eaten by a rival."

    old "Those fortunate were enslaved by humans. Those less fortunate by the orcs."
    new "Those fortunate were enslaved by humans. Those less fortunate by the orcs."

    old "On and on, the land proved a temptation that could not be resisted by those seeking better fortunes, only to betray them or their descendants in time."
    new "On and on, the land proved a temptation that could not be resisted by those seeking better fortunes, only to betray them or their descendants in time."

    old "The land itself was a trap."
    new "The land itself was a trap."

    old "This cycle continued without fail for centures, to the point some even imagined it cursed."
    new "This cycle continued without fail for centures, to the point some even imagined it cursed."

    old "But it was finally the nation of Mythra, that broke the cycle."
    new "But it was finally the nation of Mythra, that broke the cycle."

    old "Before it was a nation, it was the city of Rahayal only."
    new "Before it was a nation, it was the city of Rahayal only."

    old "But the location of the city's founding made it uniquely defensible in a land otherwise vulnerable."
    new "But the location of the city's founding made it uniquely defensible in a land otherwise vulnerable."

    old "From this position of strength, the city grew and grew."
    new "From this position of strength, the city grew and grew."

    old "This was not the first time a city had prospered for longer than usual, and so many still speculated on its inevitable defeat at the hands of man or orc."
    new "This was not the first time a city had prospered for longer than usual, and so many still speculated on its inevitable defeat at the hands of man or orc."

    old "But the defeat never came."
    new "But the defeat never came."

    old "As the city of Rahayal grew and grew, it was rather its neighbours that found themselves declining."
    new "As the city of Rahayal grew and grew, it was rather its neighbours that found themselves declining."

    old "The central kingdoms saw the rise of the city, and understood it to be a possible rival. But each time they sought to put down this new rival, they fell into infighting."
    new "The central kingdoms saw the rise of the city, and understood it to be a possible rival. But each time they sought to put down this new rival, they fell into infighting."

    old "The orc warlords saw in Rahayal a fat prize, bearing hundreds-of-thousands potential slaves and mountains of gold."
    new "The orc warlords saw in Rahayal a fat prize, bearing hundreds-of-thousands potential slaves and mountains of gold."

    old "But each time an orc chieftain tried to rally his horde, another clan declared a rivalry, or one was assassinated."
    new "But each time an orc chieftain tried to rally his horde, another clan declared a rivalry, or one was assassinated."

    old "So, round and round, the enemies of Rahayal found themselves perpetually distracted."
    new "So, round and round, the enemies of Rahayal found themselves perpetually distracted."

    old "Distracted, until one day they realized that their potential rival had grown into a real one."
    new "Distracted, until one day they realized that their potential rival had grown into a real one."

    old "By now, Rahayal had grown strong and powerful off the rich lands. Its endless fields of grain fed the mouths of millions, sustaining a population large than any that part of the world has seen."
    new "By now, Rahayal had grown strong and powerful off the rich lands. Its endless fields of grain fed the mouths of millions, sustaining a population large than any that part of the world has seen."

    old "When the enemies of Rahayal finally showed up to their gates, they found not pallisades but walls carved from stone and steel."
    new "When the enemies of Rahayal finally showed up to their gates, they found not pallisades but walls carved from stone and steel."

    old "The central kingdoms were the first to break themselves up their walls."
    new "The central kingdoms were the first to break themselves up their walls."

    old "The orc hordes, finally broken from their own civil war, flowed out from their mountains into the open fields, hungry for conquest."
    new "The orc hordes, finally broken from their own civil war, flowed out from their mountains into the open fields, hungry for conquest."

    old "But they were met out on the open fields, and their raw strength proved no match for the modern warfare of the Mythran armies."
    new "But they were met out on the open fields, and their raw strength proved no match for the modern warfare of the Mythran armies."

    old "The first legion of the Mythra broke the orcish horde in open battle, driving them back into the mountains."
    new "The first legion of the Mythra broke the orcish horde in open battle, driving them back into the mountains."

    old "And so, the enemies of Rahayal, dared not to try again."
    new "And so, the enemies of Rahayal, dared not to try again."

    old "In turn, the city surged outwards."
    new "In turn, the city surged outwards."

    old "Theirs was only the hand of violence. For as many neighbours as they conquered, so many they bribed, or annexed through trade."
    new "Theirs was only the hand of violence. For as many neighbours as they conquered, so many they bribed, or annexed through trade."

    old "In less than a century, every other power in the region had fallen under the sway of what was now officially the Mythran empire."
    new "In less than a century, every other power in the region had fallen under the sway of what was now officially the Mythran empire."

    old "Its endless fields. Its countless mines. Its unrivaled industry."
    new "Its endless fields. Its countless mines. Its unrivaled industry."

    old "Mythra became the region's superpower."
    new "Mythra became the region's superpower."

    old "The central kingdoms fell to infighting, too disunited to pose any opposition."
    new "The central kingdoms fell to infighting, too disunited to pose any opposition."

    old "The orcish horde, humiliated by their defeat, saw an endless conflict between clans and chieftains."
    new "The orcish horde, humiliated by their defeat, saw an endless conflict between clans and chieftains."

    old "Only small orc bands ever dared to leave their mountains again."
    new "Only small orc bands ever dared to leave their mountains again."

    old "Over time, they turned inward, obsessed only with fighting on another, and leaving the human world to its own designs."
    new "Over time, they turned inward, obsessed only with fighting on another, and leaving the human world to its own designs."

    old "So it came to be that the city of Rahayal grew into the empire of Mythra."
    new "So it came to be that the city of Rahayal grew into the empire of Mythra."

    old "Its capital, the crowning jewel of its empire."
    new "Its capital, the crowning jewel of its empire."

    old "The city was largely carved out of marble, giving it the appearance in daylight of almost glowing, as though it was as blessed as it pretended to be."
    new "The city was largely carved out of marble, giving it the appearance in daylight of almost glowing, as though it was as blessed as it pretended to be."

    old "The only object that defied its otherwise uniform design, was the pyramid of Rahayal."
    new "The only object that defied its otherwise uniform design, was the pyramid of Rahayal."

    old "A void-like structure, carved out of some metal or stone that existed nowhere else in the world."
    new "A void-like structure, carved out of some metal or stone that existed nowhere else in the world."

    old "Nobody knew or could tell if the pyramid had been build in the city, or if the city had been build around the pyramid."
    new "Nobody knew or could tell if the pyramid had been build in the city, or if the city had been build around the pyramid."

    old "The thing sat upon the city like a scar, dominating it, no matter from where one looked upon it."
    new "The thing sat upon the city like a scar, dominating it, no matter from where one looked upon it."

    old "To strangers and visitors, the thing was impossible to ignore. To those who lived in the city, the thing was almost impossible to notice."
    new "To strangers and visitors, the thing was impossible to ignore. To those who lived in the city, the thing was almost impossible to notice."

    old "Those most at home to the city conceived of the structure as though it was a beggar in the streets. Consciously noticed, consciously ignored."
    new "Those most at home to the city conceived of the structure as though it was a beggar in the streets. Consciously noticed, consciously ignored."

    old "Sarah too, could not ignore the thing."
    new "Sarah too, could not ignore the thing."

    old "She pointed towards the structure that seemed to eat the light around it."
    new "She pointed towards the structure that seemed to eat the light around it."

    old "That's the pyramid of Rahayal."
    new "That's the pyramid of Rahayal."

    old "That's where the Noctori live."
    new "That's where the Noctori live."

    old "Noctori?"
    new "Noctori?"

    old "Sigmund looked at her."
    new "Sigmund looked at her."

    old "You can read and write, you're educated enough, and you're telling me you don't know about them?"
    new "You can read and write, you're educated enough, and you're telling me you don't know about them?"

    old "Did they never bother to teach you any history?"
    new "Did they never bother to teach you any history?"

    old "They had, quite a lot of it in fact. But most it had revolved around the union kingdoms and Rosanna itself."
    new "They had, quite a lot of it in fact. But most it had revolved around the union kingdoms and Rosanna itself."

    old "Sarah had come to realize she really didn't know all that much about this side of the ocean."
    new "Sarah had come to realize she really didn't know all that much about this side of the ocean."

    old "Not about this place, no."
    new "Not about this place, no."

    old "Well, the Noctori are the ruling class of the Mythran empire, and that pyramid is where they hold court."
    new "Well, the Noctori are the ruling class of the Mythran empire, and that pyramid is where they hold court."

    old "The eternal court, they call it."
    new "The eternal court, they call it."

    old "The eternal court?"
    new "The eternal court?"

    old "Sigmund spat next to the wagon."
    new "Sigmund spat next to the wagon."

    old "Arrogant shit for arrogant folks. Nothin lasts forever, not even this place. But I guess they call it that, hopin to make it true."
    new "Arrogant shit for arrogant folks. Nothin lasts forever, not even this place. But I guess they call it that, hopin to make it true."

    old "Sarah looked back at the imposing structure."
    new "Sarah looked back at the imposing structure."

    old "She tried to think of the thing like a castle, the seat of power, just as her home of Castle Reinmeer had been."
    new "She tried to think of the thing like a castle, the seat of power, just as her home of Castle Reinmeer had been."

    old "Still, she struggled."
    new "Still, she struggled."

    old "The object looked too alien. Reinmeer had been a place full of warmth and life. This thing seemed devoid of either."
    new "The object looked too alien. Reinmeer had been a place full of warmth and life. This thing seemed devoid of either."

    old "Unwilling to spend much more thought on the structure, Sarah allowed her eyes to drift across the rest of Rahayal."
    new "Unwilling to spend much more thought on the structure, Sarah allowed her eyes to drift across the rest of Rahayal."

    old "Almost instantly, she felt her soul soothed."
    new "Almost instantly, she felt her soul soothed."

    old "Where the pyramid was a construct of darkness, the city was one of light."
    new "Where the pyramid was a construct of darkness, the city was one of light."

    old "Its ocean of marble and white stone reflected the rising sun, basking all of it in a glow that made Sarah feel safe and warm."
    new "Its ocean of marble and white stone reflected the rising sun, basking all of it in a glow that made Sarah feel safe and warm."

    old "A home, she thought. That's what it reminded her of."
    new "A home, she thought. That's what it reminded her of."

    old "The more she looked at the rest of the city, the easier she found it to ignore the haunting pyramid."
    new "The more she looked at the rest of the city, the easier she found it to ignore the haunting pyramid."

    old "After a while, they finally came upon the gates of the city."
    new "After a while, they finally came upon the gates of the city."

    old "The gates to the city were wide open and the city guards seemed amicable enough, standing only half-serious at their post."
    new "The gates to the city were wide open and the city guards seemed amicable enough, standing only half-serious at their post."

    old "Flowing into and out of the city was a near endless stream of caravans and wagons."
    new "Flowing into and out of the city was a near endless stream of caravans and wagons."

    old "Sarah had never seen an economy of this scale."
    new "Sarah had never seen an economy of this scale."

    old "Where on the old road they had often been alone, they were now one of a great many."
    new "Where on the old road they had often been alone, they were now one of a great many."

    old "Hardly anybody gave them a glance."
    new "Hardly anybody gave them a glance."

    old "Well, I suppose we've reached the end of our road."
    new "Well, I suppose we've reached the end of our road."

    old "Sigmund held out a bag."
    new "Sigmund held out a bag."

    old "Sarah took it from him, feeling the weight of it, she knew it was a fair bit of money."
    new "Sarah took it from him, feeling the weight of it, she knew it was a fair bit of money."

    old "Thank you, Sigmund. I really don't know what else to say."
    new "Thank you, Sigmund. I really don't know what else to say."

    old "Don't say nothing, child. You want to thank me? Just take good care of yourself, that's all I want for you."
    new "Don't say nothing, child. You want to thank me? Just take good care of yourself, that's all I want for you."

    old "I will, I promise."
    new "I will, I promise."

    old "Enter Rahayal"
    new "Enter Rahayal"

    old "Sarah said her goodbyes to Sigmund, Sakar and Krip."
    new "Sarah said her goodbyes to Sigmund, Sakar and Krip."

    old "To her surprise, even Krip offered her a few words of good luck."
    new "To her surprise, even Krip offered her a few words of good luck."

    old "Finally, with nothing left to be done or said, Sarah waved at the men she had come to consider friends, and walked off into the crowd."
    new "Finally, with nothing left to be done or said, Sarah waved at the men she had come to consider friends, and walked off into the crowd."

    old "Before long, so many people flanked her from every side, she could no longer turn around and see them."
    new "Before long, so many people flanked her from every side, she could no longer turn around and see them."

    old "She wondered if she ever would see them again."
    new "She wondered if she ever would see them again."

